that people
view institutions and the sense
of distrust

21:07.066 --> 21:12.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and dysfunction about whether
it's about government,
whether it's about corporations,
whether it's

21:12.171 --> 21:13.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about the media.

21:13.806 --> 21:18.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so any appearance of
impropriety is going
to be taken very, very
seriously.

21:18.177 --> 21:23.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The issue now -- or the
watchword really is
transparency, authenticity.

21:23.115 --> 21:27.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those are things that have been
missing from
the Clinton campaign and from,
quite frankly

21:27.386 --> 21:31.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the way that Hillary Clinton has
done her
job as secretary of state, and
then the Clinton

21:31.223 --> 21:33.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Global Initiative from the very
beginning.

21:33.859 --> 21:39.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the expectations are very
different, and
they're not meeting those
expectations.

21:39.698 --> 21:42.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Some of these
themes just keep
on popping up again and again.

21:42.034 --> 21:43.202 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: It's exactly right.

21:43.235 --> 21:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you think we're going to see
the end it
-- it's not.

21:44.937 --> 21:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Amy Walter,
Tamara Keith, we
thank you.

21:48.307 --> 21:53.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: Thank you.

21:53.245 --> 21:58.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: You're welcome.

21:58.150 --> 22:01.220 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

22:01.253 --> 22:06.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
what a judge's
ruling means for President
Obama's order on

22:06.058 --> 22:13.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
transgender students; a jihadist
charged with
war crimes for destroying
ancient monuments;

22:13.265 --> 22:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and a Massachusetts couple's
plan to end hunger
and keep their son's memory
alive.

22:18.904 --> 22:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: Virtually every day,
the skies
over Northern Syria are filled
with Russian

22:24.843 --> 22:30.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Assad regime jets, and,
often, the bombs
they drop land on civilians.

22:30.182 --> 22:33.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is no 911 to dial, and no
one to call
for help.

22:33.719 --> 22:38.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But people do come rushing to
save them, and
more often than not, the
rescuers are Syrians

22:38.757 --> 22:40.593 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
wearing white helmets.

22:40.626 --> 22:46.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are ordinary men and women
who've chosen
to stay, pressed into service by
circumstance,

22:46.832 --> 22:50.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
charged with saving their fellow
Syrians amid
a brutal war.

22:50.436 --> 22:55.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We meet some of them now, thanks
to special
correspondent Marcia Biggs, who
reports from

22:55.641 --> 22:57.409 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Turkey.

22:57.443 --> 23:03.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: We all saw this
heartbreaking
video, 5-year-old Omran pulled
from under

23:03.716 --> 23:07.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the rubble of his flattened
home, his photo
going viral.

23:07.386 --> 23:13.726 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stunned, bloodied, and caked
with dust, his
face a symbol of so many others.

23:13.759 --> 23:18.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the faces you didn't see in
this video
are of those who have been
pulling people

23:18.330 --> 23:24.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out of the rubble for five long
years.

23:24.670 --> 23:30.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the call to work for the
brave members
of the Syrian Civil Defense, an
ad hoc grassroots

23:30.409 --> 23:33.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
first-response unit within
rebel-held Syria.

23:33.512 --> 23:39.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nicknamed the White Helmets,
they rush toward
the scene of a bombing to save
victims, many

23:39.618 --> 23:46.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of whom are trapped under
rubble, once tailors,
bakers, pharmacists, these 3,000
ordinary

23:46.592 --> 23:50.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Syrian men and some women now
unwitting heroes.

23:50.329 --> 23:56.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Twenty-three-year-old Radi Saad
was a topography
student at Aleppo University
itching to get

23:56.302 --> 24:00.306 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
out of Syria, when the
revolution began and
his life changed.

24:00.339 --> 24:04.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He now lives in Turkey, but
travels back and
forth to Syria to volunteer.

24:04.076 --> 24:08.714 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RADI SAAD, Rescue Worker
(through translator):
I never thought about being a
search-and-rescue

24:08.747 --> 24:09.715 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
worker.

24:09.748 --> 24:11.383 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That idea didn't exist in Syria.

24:11.417 --> 24:15.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During shelling or after an
airstrike, all
the people come out to save
lives.

24:15.587 --> 24:19.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When someone in need comes to
you, would you
say, I have nothing to offer
you?

24:19.825 --> 24:21.560 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So then why am I here?

24:21.593 --> 24:23.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a question I asked
myself.

24:23.796 --> 24:27.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was three years ago, and I
have been
working in civil defense ever
since.

24:27.666 --> 24:33.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: They work under
the harshest
of conditions to claw through
the remains

24:33.172 --> 24:38.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of buildings flattened by the
Syrian regime's
weapon of choice, the barrel
bomb, a crudely

24:38.911 --> 24:43.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made drum packed with explosives
and nails,
indiscriminately rolled out the
back of a

24:43.816 --> 24:51.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
helicopter over civilian areas,
the slow and
silent descent a cruel harbinger
of the devastation

24:51.056 --> 24:53.892 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it creates.

24:53.926 --> 25:03.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RADI SAAD (through translator):
The hardest
part is to get people under the
rubble out.

25:03.602 --> 25:07.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's exhausting, and you don't
have technical
equipment to use.

25:07.473 --> 25:08.974 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have simple equipment.

25:09.007 --> 25:14.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Often, the process of searching
and rescuing
takes 30 or 40 continuous hours.

25:14.213 --> 25:18.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You get tired, but the hope
inside you makes
you forget, and you just keep
going to try

25:18.584 --> 25:21.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to reach the person who needs
your help.

25:21.420 --> 25:24.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Not all stories
have a happy
ending.

25:24.656 --> 25:29.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Radi remembers searching in vain
for 25 hours
for a 2-month-old child.

25:29.661 --> 25:34.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RADI SAAD (through translator):
His father
came to me, and I was the team
leader.

25:34.400 --> 25:38.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was begging me, not to
continue trying
to find his son.

25:38.370 --> 25:42.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No, he just wanted me to find
any piece of
his son's body.

25:42.908 --> 25:45.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These were moments I would never
forget.

25:45.244 --> 25:46.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You're not thinking.

25:46.678 --> 25:49.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're in a huge disaster, so
you don't think
about what's happening.

25:49.548 --> 25:50.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Your emotions go away.

25:50.682 --> 25:52.484 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You don't have them anymore.

25:52.518 --> 25:56.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I got home that night, I
remembered,
and I felt the same feeling I
have now.

25:56.488 --> 25:57.723 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I was shocked.

25:57.756 --> 25:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do we have any feeling left?

25:59.892 --> 26:01.794 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Have we lost our feelings?

26:01.827 --> 26:05.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Has the hope become about
finding a piece
of a loved one, a body part?

26:05.497 --> 26:09.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even now, I can't comprehend the
situation
I was in or what happened.

26:09.435 --> 26:17.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: But what makes it
one of the
most dangerous jobs in the
world, the infamous

26:17.576 --> 26:23.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
double tap, when planes circle
back after
the original strike to target
rescue workers

26:23.882 --> 26:29.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
racing to the scene.

26:29.688 --> 26:34.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last October, White Helmets were
responding
to this bombing in Idlib
province when Russian

26:34.693 --> 26:39.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
jets circled back, killing
31-year-old Issam
al-Saleh (ph).

26:39.865 --> 26:45.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RADI SAAD (through translator):
I heard that
Russian airstrikes targeted a
farm with women

26:45.871 --> 26:48.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and children, so I jumped in the
car and went.

26:48.340 --> 26:50.642 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I couldn't drive fast enough.

26:50.676 --> 26:55.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I arrived, no one was
there, just people
under the rubble, but the jets
were coming

26:55.180 --> 26:56.582 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
back.

26:56.615 --> 26:59.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I heard that Issam had
died, it was a
big shock.

26:59.418 --> 27:03.155 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
When we buried him, we all
started crying.

27:03.188 --> 27:04.990 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Issam was like a brother to me.

27:05.023 --> 27:10.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Issam's cousin,
Raed Al Saleh,
is the head of Syrian Civil
Defense, like

27:10.062 --> 27:14.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most White Helmets, thrust into
a job he never
dreamed he'd have.

27:14.132 --> 27:16.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAED AL SALEH, Director, Syrian
Civil Defense
(through translator): Actually,
my work in

27:16.668 --> 27:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
civil defense just kind of
happened.

27:18.904 --> 27:24.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At that time, none of us in
Syria knew anything
about civil defense, or how this
work is done.

27:25.010 --> 27:26.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we went to a training in
Istanbul.

27:26.745 --> 27:31.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A trainer put us in a dark room
and asked
what we were able to find.

27:31.917 --> 27:36.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We said there was just debris,
but then he
turned on the light and we
realized there

27:36.321 --> 27:39.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were people pretending to be
wounded.

27:39.191 --> 27:41.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It shocked us that we hadn't
found them.

27:41.660 --> 27:45.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We decided then and there that
we had to be
serious about our training.

27:45.464 --> 27:51.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Your mother or mine, your sister
or brother,
your friend could be under the
rubble, and

27:51.370 --> 27:53.772 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if they are not found, they will
die.

27:53.805 --> 28:00.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Over the last five
years, they
say they have learned, saving
almost 60,000

28:00.312 --> 28:06.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lives, working throughout all
parts of one
of the most fractured areas on
Earth.

28:06.218 --> 28:09.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even some of the most radical
groups allow
them into their territory.

28:09.354 --> 28:13.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): To serve
the civilians in the regions
under control

28:13.258 --> 28:19.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of armed groups, we have no
choice but to
deal with such groups in order
to do our work.

28:19.565 --> 28:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This happens all over Syria.

28:21.667 --> 28:26.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We make it clear to all that we
don't make
any official links with any
political or military

28:27.005 --> 28:28.707 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a group in Syria.

28:28.740 --> 28:31.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Do you have any
agreement with
ISIS to be able to work in those
areas?

28:31.643 --> 28:35.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): We go
and say we will offer our
services.

28:35.314 --> 28:37.516 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
If you allow us to do so, fine.

28:37.549 --> 28:39.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
If you don't, off we go.

28:39.251 --> 28:43.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Has any other
group this large
been able to unify in rebel-held
Syria?

28:43.422 --> 28:47.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): All over
Syria, there is no other
organization that

28:47.893 --> 28:52.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
offers these services and works
under one
management, other than the
Syrian Civil Defense.

28:52.798 --> 28:57.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Their tenacious
leader has gone
all over the world, begging for
an end to

28:57.803 --> 29:03.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the violence, last year, an
impassioned speech
at the United Nations, this year
nominated

29:03.141 --> 29:06.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for the Nobel Peace Prize, all
to no avail.

29:06.478 --> 29:11.717 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): In all
my speeches, I was delivering a
message to

29:11.750 --> 29:14.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the people, to be in solidarity
with us.

29:14.386 --> 29:17.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I wasn't asking politicians to
do that.

29:17.723 --> 29:20.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Politicians aren't concerned
about human suffering.

29:20.359 --> 29:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't look at the problem
and get involved
to solve it.

29:23.328 --> 29:26.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They see the problems as
opportunities, to
see what they can get out of
them.

29:26.898 --> 29:28.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARCIA BIGGS: Is anyone
listening to you?

29:28.734 --> 29:32.137 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): We hope
there are people listening to
us.

29:32.170 --> 29:37.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We hope the people will stand by
us, to pressure
politicians to change their
policies, which

29:37.075 --> 29:42.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
only benefit politicians, and
instead to base
those policies on human rights
and to take

29:42.848 --> 29:46.385 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
into account the crimes
committed against
civilians all over the world.

29:46.418 --> 29:48.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Do you feel like
you're banging
your head against a wall?

29:48.920 --> 29:52.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): Actually,
I used to feel like I was
hitting my head

29:52.924 --> 29:54.159 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
against a wall.

29:54.192 --> 29:56.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now I feel like I'm hitting my
head against
iron.

29:56.294 --> 30:01.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: So, how do you
keep going when
no one is listening?

30:01.133 --> 30:03.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): We have
to.

30:03.368 --> 30:07.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What keeps us going are the
people we save
from the rubble.

30:07.239 --> 30:10.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People in Syria see us as the
hope that keeps
them alive.

30:10.308 --> 30:16.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: One of their most
hopeful moments
came in the summer of 2014;
29-year-old Khaled

30:16.148 --> 30:21.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Omar Harrah had already been
digging through
the rubble for nine hours when
he heard the

30:21.553 --> 30:24.723 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
faint sounds of a baby crying.

30:24.756 --> 30:30.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Only two weeks old, baby Mahmud
was trapped
under three stories of a
collapsed building.

30:30.228 --> 30:36.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For several more hours, they
gingerly dug,
finally pulling him out alive.

30:36.635 --> 30:43.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Khaled's video went viral, and
he was nicknamed
the baby savior.

30:43.775 --> 30:48.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, in Syria, cruelty lies
around every corner.

30:48.413 --> 30:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just over a week ago, Khaled was
killed in
an airstrike, joining the other
134 White

30:54.352 --> 30:56.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Helmets that have lost their
lives.

30:56.755 --> 31:03.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Khaled's unit was based in
rebel-held Aleppo,
which has been besieged for over
a month by

31:03.628 --> 31:09.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government forces, which allow
no food or
medical aid to the over 300,000
civilians

31:09.401 --> 31:11.169 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
trapped inside.

31:11.203 --> 31:15.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The head of the Aleppo unit
recently sent
to the United Nations Security
Council this

31:15.474 --> 31:17.142 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
video.

31:17.175 --> 31:19.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Throughout the message, a battle
rages in
the background.

31:19.778 --> 31:30.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): What
broke our hearts
is that we heard nothing from
the U.N.

31:30.288 --> 31:34.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Abdul Rahman, a
30-year-old
volunteer from Aleppo, says the
food shortage

31:34.426 --> 31:39.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a main concern and half of
the men in the
unit are trying to learn to
farm.

31:39.331 --> 31:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are they worried that they might
starve?

31:41.767 --> 31:43.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Are they worried that they're
going to run
out of food?

31:43.535 --> 31:48.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABDUL RAHMAN, Rescue Worker: Of
course, but
they're still working, because
we believe

31:48.240 --> 31:49.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in our job.

31:49.241 --> 31:50.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They lost the hope.

31:50.742 --> 31:51.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is the bigger problem.

31:51.943 --> 31:56.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, in Aleppo city, all the
world see the
besieged.

31:56.681 --> 32:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all the world just watching
what happened,
and no one do anything.

32:00.485 --> 32:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Despite all the
deaths and the
failures of the international
community, the

32:05.724 --> 32:07.626 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
White Helmets soldier on.

32:07.659 --> 32:14.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAED AL SALEH (through
translator): It's difficult
to talk with our team everyday,
and most of

32:14.332 --> 32:17.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the time, we have no answers to
all the questions
they ask.

32:17.602 --> 32:23.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are doing an important
humanitarian job,
and we will be rewarded by God.

32:23.608 --> 32:29.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Koran says, in the name of
God, the most
gracious, the most merciful,
whosoever saveth

32:29.514 --> 32:34.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the life of one, it shall be as
if he had
saved the life of all mankind.

32:34.252 --> 32:38.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you save a human who was
under the rubble,
it's like you saved all mankind.

32:38.456 --> 32:43.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you feel proud when you wear
that?

32:43.762 --> 32:48.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For Radi, his uniform a symbol
of pride, and
for the young man who dreamed of
one day getting

32:48.967 --> 32:55.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of Syria, a renewed pride in
his country,
which he and the others hope to
someday rebuild.

32:55.173 --> 33:00.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RADI SAAD (through translator):
Before the
revolution, we didn't have a
sense of belonging

33:00.245 --> 33:01.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to this country at all.

33:01.947 --> 33:05.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But now we feel that, if we
don't build this
country, no one will.

33:05.917 --> 33:09.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: A small glimmer of
hope for
the future.

33:09.921 --> 33:16.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For now, every airstrike brings
more devastation,
and the men, like this one,
Fares Mohammed

33:16.428 --> 33:22.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ali, who dig with their hands
and their hearts
to raise people out of the ruins
and into

33:22.100 --> 33:24.302 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the light.

33:24.336 --> 33:27.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One can only wonder how long
this light of
hope can burn.

33:27.939 --> 33:30.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Fares died last month after an
airstrike.

33:30.475 --> 33:41.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Marcia Biggs in
Istanbul, Turkey.

33:41.853 --> 33:51.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The decision by a
Texas judge
to block the Obama
administration's rules

33:51.496 --> 33:57.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on transgender bathrooms and
locker rooms
comes just as the school year is
starting.

33:57.469 --> 34:02.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's coming as many school
districts are
trying to determine what to do
now.

34:02.274 --> 34:04.142 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has our update.

34:04.175 --> 34:08.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This ruling is
the second
setback in recent weeks for
transgender advocates.

34:08.480 --> 34:12.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Earlier this month, the Supreme
Court said
a Virginia school board could
block a transgender

34:12.951 --> 34:17.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
student from using the boys
bathroom while
the higher court decides if it
will take up

34:17.055 --> 34:18.857 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
these broader case.

34:18.890 --> 34:22.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yesterday's decision is the
first to say that
the Obama administration's
directive could

34:22.260 --> 34:24.162 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be blocked nationwide.

34:24.195 --> 34:28.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those directives instructed
school districts
to allow trans students to use
the bathroom

34:28.199 --> 34:29.768 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of their choice.

34:29.801 --> 34:33.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Texas is one of 13 states
challenging the
constitutionality of the
directive.

34:33.838 --> 34:38.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this case, the judge wrote
that the administration
had exceeded its authority under
Title IX,

34:38.910 --> 34:42.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the 1970s-era law banning sex
discrimination
in schools.

34:42.247 --> 34:46.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help us wade through the
meaning of all
this, I'm joined now by Evie
Blad, who is

34:46.318 --> 34:49.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Education Week reporter
who's been covering
this story.

34:49.120 --> 34:53.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Evie, what does this ruling
say, and how
significant is this?

34:53.158 --> 34:57.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD, Education Week: It's
very significant,
in that it's the first time we
have heard

34:57.128 --> 35:00.665 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a federal court weigh in on a
nationwide basis.

35:00.699 --> 35:06.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are several cases winding
their way
through the federal courts now,
but the only

35:06.705 --> 35:11.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one that has had a ruling so far
applied only
in one circuit.

35:11.876 --> 35:17.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's significant, in that
the school year
is about to start, and this
judge is saying,

35:17.349 --> 35:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nationwide, that the Obama
administration's
regulations under Title IX, its
civil rights

35:22.921 --> 35:25.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
guidance, doesn't need to be
implemented.

35:25.757 --> 35:31.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So what that means is if a
school doesn't
want to create a policy allowing
transgender

35:31.429 --> 35:34.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students to use the rest room of
their choice,
it doesn't have to.

35:34.165 --> 35:40.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if a school has a policy
that it wants
to have, it can keep that
policy.

35:40.105 --> 35:42.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It just doesn't have a federal
directive to
do so.

35:42.507 --> 35:46.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, Texas was
one of a bunch
of states that had objection to
these rules.

35:46.611 --> 35:48.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the essence of their
objection?

35:48.813 --> 35:53.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Well, there are two
primary things
that you will see in these
lawsuits.

35:53.952 --> 35:57.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One is something that we're all
familiar with,
which is the argument that folks
are making

35:57.489 --> 35:59.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
about privacy rights of
students.

35:59.791 --> 36:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does my student or my child who
isn't transgender
have a right to use a restroom
that doesn't

36:08.166 --> 36:09.534 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have transgender students in it?

36:09.567 --> 36:11.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Right.

36:11.436 --> 36:14.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
EVIE BLAD: There is some
discomfort because
some students who have undergone
gender transitions

36:14.439 --> 36:16.174 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
haven't undergone sex
transitions.

36:16.207 --> 36:18.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so there's some discomfort
there.

36:18.376 --> 36:21.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the primary argument is one
of legal interpretation.

36:21.913 --> 36:28.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, when the Obama
administration
created the civil rights
guidance, did it

36:28.386 --> 36:33.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
interpret an existing
regulation, which is
what it argues it did, or, what
the states

36:33.625 --> 36:39.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
argue that it did is that it
created a new
one under the guise of
interpreting law.

36:39.164 --> 36:44.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it was to create a new
policy, the
states argue that it should have
gone through

36:44.669 --> 36:50.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Administrative Procedures
Act, and given
them time to comment and weigh
in on the issue.

36:50.308 --> 36:54.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, that's
what the judge
said in this case, that the way
the Obama

36:54.479 --> 36:58.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
administration went about
issuing the directive
was what was illegal, in its
view?

36:58.983 --> 37:03.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Yes, he said that the
states had
proven that there's merit to
this case, so

37:03.655 --> 37:04.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it's worth hearing.

37:04.656 --> 37:06.558 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, this is a temporary delay.

37:06.591 --> 37:12.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what he's doing is, he's
halting the directive
until he has a chance to hear
and weigh in

37:12.097 --> 37:13.898 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the full case.

37:13.932 --> 37:23.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, yes, he said his order was
pretty clear
that they may have violated the
Administrative

37:23.274 --> 37:25.110 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Procedures Act.

37:25.143 --> 37:28.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So that's the
judge's ruling,
but as we have seen with a lot
of these laws

37:28.446 --> 37:33.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around the country, some of the
resistance
to them comes from the belief
that somehow

37:33.918 --> 37:39.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if these laws are passed, that
men, not transgender
men, are going to somehow dress
up as women

37:39.791 --> 37:43.027 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and go into the women's
restrooms.

37:43.061 --> 37:46.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there any evidence that that
kind of activity
actually goes on?

37:46.798 --> 37:48.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVIE BLAD: Right.

37:48.600 --> 37:52.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, and the argument at the
school level
is oftentimes that boys will
decide one day

37:52.770 --> 37:56.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be one thing and another
thing, that there
will be some mischievousness,
right?

37:56.407 --> 38:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, long before the federal
regulations
came out, or long before the
Obama administration

38:02.313 --> 38:08.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
began asserting these things in
courts, school
districts were making these
decisions on their

38:08.753 --> 38:09.721 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
own.

38:09.754 --> 38:11.289 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, L.A. Unified, for example,
the second...

38:11.322 --> 38:13.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Los Angeles.

38:13.091 --> 38:15.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Yes, the second
largest district
in the country, for more than a
decade, has

38:15.760 --> 38:20.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had a policy that allowed
transgender students
to use the restroom that aligned
with their

38:20.098 --> 38:21.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
gender identity.

38:21.900 --> 38:28.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
L.A. Unified says that they can
count on one
hand the numbers of times a
student has had

38:28.039 --> 38:33.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to clarify these accommodations
in administrative
offices.

38:33.144 --> 38:39.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And they don't have any
documented incidents
of problems, the last time I
checked.

38:39.083 --> 38:42.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Part of the problem here is that
we are talking
to districts who are oftentimes
defending

38:42.654 --> 38:45.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
policies they feel very strongly
about.

38:45.456 --> 38:49.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some opponents of these policies
may say,
even if there aren't these big
documented

38:49.994 --> 38:54.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
problems, that they still feel
that their
students have some privacy
interests here

38:54.299 --> 38:56.034 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that need to be respected.

38:56.067 --> 39:00.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, if I'm a
transgender
student and I start school
tomorrow, next

39:00.238 --> 39:03.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
week, two weeks from now, what
does this ruling
mean for me?

39:03.708 --> 39:05.443 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVIE BLAD: Right.

39:05.476 --> 39:12.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, if your school doesn't
have a policy
that directs what restroom
you're allowed

39:12.317 --> 39:20.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to use, you don't have the
ability to take
enforcement through the
Department of Education,

39:20.925 --> 39:24.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because the judge has said you
can't enforce
this directive.

39:24.696 --> 39:28.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Previously, a transgender
student could go
to the department and say: I
feel like my

39:28.700 --> 39:30.768 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
civil rights are being violated.

39:30.802 --> 39:34.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, that has been put on
hold through
this order.

39:34.939 --> 39:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Transgender students say that
bathrooms are
not their only concern in
school, sort of

39:39.711 --> 39:43.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
feeling safe and a sense of
belonging, but
they say that they do matter,
because when

39:43.648 --> 39:47.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a school doesn't allow them to
use the restroom
of their choice or requires them
to use a

39:47.919 --> 39:52.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
single stall or staff restroom,
they say that
it feels like the school isn't
respecting

39:52.423 --> 39:54.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their gender transition.

39:54.292 --> 39:58.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that can stigmatize them or
bring other
school climate concerns with
their classmates.

39:58.062 --> 40:02.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, there's a
lot of different
legal cases going on, in Texas,
and Virginia

40:02.800 --> 40:04.535 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and other places.

40:04.569 --> 40:09.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is your sense, is the legal
analysis here
that this is ultimately going to
end up at

40:09.040 --> 40:10.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Supreme Court?

40:10.842 --> 40:14.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: There's a lot of
folks in school
law who felt that it was bound
for that for

40:14.178 --> 40:16.014 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a long time.

40:16.047 --> 40:20.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a decision in Virginia
that the school
court -- the Supreme Court has
put a temporary

40:20.818 --> 40:24.055 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
hold on that case.

40:24.088 --> 40:28.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In that instance, the court of
appeals sided
with the Obama administration on
these rules

40:28.393 --> 40:31.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and said that it is an
appropriate interpretation
of Title IX.

40:32.030 --> 40:36.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the Supreme Court put a
temporary halt
on that while it decides whether
it is going

40:36.968 --> 40:39.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to consider the issue in its
next term.

40:39.504 --> 40:41.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In that case, we could get an
ultimate decision.

40:41.806 --> 40:46.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even if the Supreme Court
decides not to take
up that case, we could see
differing issues

40:46.177 --> 40:48.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- differing opinions on the
circuit court
level.

40:48.980 --> 40:53.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in that case, a lot of
times, those issues
end up going to the Supreme
Court for further

40:53.217 --> 40:54.385 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
clarity.

40:54.419 --> 40:56.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, chances are, it might end up
there sooner
or later.

40:56.788 --> 41:00.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Evie Blad of
Education Week, thank you very
much.

41:00.992 --> 41:08.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVIE BLAD: Thank you.

41:08.366 --> 41:16.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's a first for
the International
Criminal Court at The Hague, a
trial dealing

41:16.474 --> 41:19.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with the destruction of cultural
heritage..

41:19.477 --> 41:24.349 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's over the deliberate
wrecking in 2012
of historic earthen buildings
and religious

41:24.382 --> 41:28.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shrines in the West African
nation of Mali.

41:28.186 --> 41:29.721 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

41:29.754 --> 41:33.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of our ongoing series
Culture at
Risk.

41:33.658 --> 41:40.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Sixty holy tombs
dating back
to the 14th century, all reduced
to rubble

41:40.298 --> 41:46.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in a wave of violence unleashed
on Timbuktu
by Islamist militants four years
ago.

41:46.170 --> 41:51.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, one of those responsible
stood in front
of the International Criminal
Court and admitted

41:51.509 --> 41:53.244 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his guilt.

41:53.277 --> 41:55.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
AHMAD AL FAQI AL MAHDI,
Defendant (through
translator): I regret all the
damage that

41:55.680 --> 41:57.415 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
my actions have caused.

41:57.448 --> 42:01.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I regret what I have caused to
my family,
my community in Timbuktu, what I
have caused

42:01.753 --> 42:03.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
my home nation, Mali.

42:03.588 --> 42:08.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Prosecutors say
Ahmad Al Faqi
Al Mahdi directed the
destruction of nine

42:08.426 --> 42:11.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mausoleums and damage to a
mosque.

42:11.295 --> 42:16.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He'd been recruited to lead a
vice squad by
a group of Islamist rebels,
affiliated with

42:16.334 --> 42:19.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
al-Qaida, who seized control of
Northern Mali
in 2012.

42:19.871 --> 42:24.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AHMAD AL FAQI AL MAHDI (through
translator):
I was influenced by a group of
deviant people

42:24.442 --> 42:29.147 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from al-Qaida, and they were
able to influence
me, to carry me in their evil
wave, through

42:29.180 --> 42:31.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actions that affected the whole
population.

42:31.282 --> 42:36.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The rebels were
eventually
driven out by French troops in
2013.

42:36.053 --> 42:42.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The heaps of rubble they left
behind have
since mostly been rebuilt with
help from UNESCO.

42:42.660 --> 42:47.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In recent years, cultural relics
across Northern
Africa and the Mideast have been
targeted

42:47.598 --> 42:53.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
by militant groups, most
dramatically by the
Islamic State at sites including
the ancient

42:53.337 --> 42:57.608 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
cities of Palmyra, Syria, and
Nimrud in Iraq.

42:57.642 --> 43:01.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Unlike Mali, those countries are
not subject
to the jurisdiction of the ICC.

43:01.746 --> 43:08.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mahdi, who, in the plea bargain
faces 11 years
in prison, today called for an
end to such

43:08.553 --> 43:10.288 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
acts.

43:10.321 --> 43:12.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AHMAD AL FAQI AL MAHDI (through
translator):
I would like to give a piece of
advice to

43:12.723 --> 43:17.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Muslims all over the world, not
to get involved
in the same acts I got involved
in, because

43:17.795 --> 43:20.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they are not going to lead to
any good to
humanity.

43:20.331 --> 43:24.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Human rights
groups say Mahdi
and others also committed crimes
against the

43:24.402 --> 43:28.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
local community, including rape
and sexual
slavery.

43:28.306 --> 43:32.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The ICC says further charges may
follow.

43:32.376 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for more on this case and
its broader
implications, we're joined by
Patty Gerstenblith.

43:36.681 --> 43:41.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's a professor of law at
DePaul University
and head of its Center for Art,
Museum and

43:41.586 --> 43:43.221 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Cultural Heritage Law.

43:43.254 --> 43:45.022 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Welcome to you.

43:45.056 --> 43:49.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First thing I want to ask is,
how significant
is this case as a war crime
prosecution?

43:49.160 --> 43:52.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PATTY GERSTENBLITH, DePaul
University: Yes,
it is very significant.

43:52.330 --> 43:58.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the first case that we have
on an international
level where somebody was
prosecuted only for

43:58.870 --> 44:01.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the crime of destruction of
cultural heritage.

44:01.506 --> 44:06.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have other examples of
prosecutions during
the World War II and the Balkan
conflict,

44:06.611 --> 44:11.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but in all those cases, the
defendants had
committed a variety of war
crimes and crimes

44:11.749 --> 44:18.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against humanity, things like
mass killings
of civilians, rapes, things like
that.

44:18.723 --> 44:23.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is the first case we
have where the
defendant was charged only with
destruction

44:23.928 --> 44:25.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of cultural heritage.

44:25.730 --> 44:30.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I believe it's significant
because it
sends a message that the
international community

44:30.134 --> 44:33.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will take these kinds of crimes,
these kind
of destructions seriously.

44:33.938 --> 44:39.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why has it taken
so long, or
why is it so hard to bring these
kind of cases?

44:39.877 --> 44:44.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is it the lack of the law or the
lack of the
will to bring these cases?

44:44.949 --> 44:47.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PATTY GERSTENBLITH: I would say
it's a variety.

44:47.818 --> 44:53.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The laws, until this point, have
been based
-- or the prosecutions have been
based on

44:53.724 --> 44:58.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
special criminal tribunals that
were set up,
such as the Nuremberg tribunal
and the International

44:58.930 --> 45:03.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia
following the Balkan conflict.

45:03.034 --> 45:07.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as I said, in those cases,
there were
many, many things, horrible
things that were

45:07.672 --> 45:11.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
done, of which cultural property
destruction
was just one.

45:11.375 --> 45:15.746 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, unfortunately, the
international community
didn't always regard the
cultural heritage

45:15.780 --> 45:21.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
destruction as necessarily the
most significant
of the different kinds of crimes
that were

45:21.953 --> 45:23.854 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
committed.

45:23.888 --> 45:27.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We now have the structure of the
International
Criminal Court established by
the Rome Statute.

45:27.858 --> 45:30.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's where this particular
prosecution
was brought.

45:30.895 --> 45:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is always the problem that
different
countries have ratified
different international

45:35.766 --> 45:37.635 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
conventions.

45:37.668 --> 45:42.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you can only bring a
prosecution when
a country has ratified the
appropriate instrument.

45:42.239 --> 45:46.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In this case, Mali is a member
of the International
Criminal Court.

45:47.011 --> 45:53.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It has ratified the Rome
Statute, which made
this feasible under this
particular legislation.

45:53.217 --> 46:01.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This perhaps at this point was
brought as
a sole charge, sole crime,
because of what

46:01.158 --> 46:05.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're witnessing going on,
particularly in
the Middle East, where we have
the Islamic

46:05.529 --> 46:11.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
State carrying out large-scale
destruction
of cultural and religious sites.

46:11.135 --> 46:16.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has not been seen on this
kind of a level
with this much publicity in a
long time, and

46:16.841 --> 46:20.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
certainly not things that we
have seen in
real time happening.

46:20.511 --> 46:23.881 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the world has stood by and
seen this happen.

46:23.914 --> 46:29.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now we have finally been
able to send
a message that these kinds of
destructions

46:29.387 --> 46:31.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will be taken seriously by the
international
community.

46:31.922 --> 46:38.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, when you look
at this specific
Timbuktu case, though, can you
say why it

46:38.529 --> 46:39.497 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was successful?

46:39.530 --> 46:41.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Are there particulars there?

46:41.332 --> 46:46.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before we use it to see how it
might look
to other cases, what happened
there?

46:46.671 --> 46:49.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATTY GERSTENBLITH: Well, I
think one of the
most important things that made
this case

46:49.940 --> 46:54.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
feasible, first of all, the law
was in place,
as I mentioned, the
international law.

46:54.645 --> 47:00.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secondly, it happened that Mr.
Al Mahdi was
apprehended in a different
country, but he

47:00.651 --> 47:03.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was then turned over to the
International
Criminal Court.

47:03.788 --> 47:08.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think the most important
thing from
a straight factual or
evidentiary perspective

47:08.192 --> 47:14.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that there were films that
were made, videos
that were made of him destroying
and directing

47:14.198 --> 47:19.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the destruction, and, in fact,
bragging about
his role in destroying these
sites, because,

47:19.136 --> 47:23.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
remember that, in a lot of these
cases, it's
-- when a case is brought
sometimes years

47:23.274 --> 47:28.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after something has been done,
proving exactly
who did what becomes difficult.

47:28.412 --> 47:30.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we can have documentation
that a site was
destroyed.

47:30.915 --> 47:35.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can say, oh, this clearly
violated international
law, but proving exactly who and
under what

47:35.886 --> 47:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
circumstances did it, proving
the intentionality,
and then proving the identity of
the person

47:41.625 --> 47:43.394 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who carried it out.

47:43.427 --> 47:49.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for example, in the Balkan
cases, the
cases of destruction in Bosnia
and in Croatia,

47:49.200 --> 47:53.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it was often difficult to
determine exactly
who was responsible, who gave
the order, who

47:53.971 --> 47:55.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
carried it out.

47:55.740 --> 47:57.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And was it intentional?

47:57.408 --> 48:01.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And also I guess another
important aspect
is that there was no armed
conflict going

48:01.579 --> 48:05.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on at the time that the shrines
in Timbuktu
were destroyed.

48:05.516 --> 48:11.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In most cases, destruction of
cultural heritage
can be excused to what's called
military necessity.

48:11.789 --> 48:18.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was an example in Timbuktu
where there
was clearly no military
necessity for carrying

48:18.362 --> 48:20.131 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
out the destruction.

48:20.164 --> 48:23.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: You have
mentioned -- and,
of course, we have reported on
these dramatic

48:23.167 --> 48:30.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cases in Syria and Iraq and
elsewhere -- the
widespread scale of them now.

48:30.241 --> 48:35.346 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Can you see this case in
Timbuktu as a real
precedent that might have an
impact?

48:35.379 --> 48:38.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PATTY GERSTENBLITH: I certainly
think it is
a precedent.

48:38.816 --> 48:40.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a very good precedent.

48:40.751 --> 48:46.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether it will have an impact
is always difficult
to tell, because, presumably,
the Islamic

48:46.390 --> 48:50.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
State members who are carrying
out the most
egregious of the destruction,
maybe they're

48:50.594 --> 48:54.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not worried about whether some
day they will
be brought before a criminal
tribunal.

48:54.665 --> 48:58.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It will be difficult to tell
exactly who ordered
the destruction.

48:58.269 --> 49:03.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I also think that there is a
message that
other destructions, particularly
in Syria,

49:03.107 --> 49:09.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for example, being carried out
by the Assad
regime, perhaps accidentally,
perhaps intentionally,

49:09.079 --> 49:13.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
perhaps negligently or an
extreme form of
negligence.

49:13.684 --> 49:19.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I hope the message is going
not only to
the obvious examples of the
Islamic State,

49:20.024 --> 49:26.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but also to other governments,
to other individuals
who also are carrying out or are
responsible

49:26.330 --> 49:28.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for this kind of heritage
destruction.

49:28.098 --> 49:30.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Patty
Gerstenblith, thank you
very much.

49:30.668 --> 49:31.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PATTY GERSTENBLITH: Sure.

49:31.735 --> 49:37.942 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you, Jeff.

49:37.975 --> 49:48.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One Massachusetts
couple is
on a mission to end hunger in
their town of

49:48.052 --> 49:51.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Framingham about 20 miles
outside of Boston.

49:51.722 --> 49:57.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Tina Martin from PBS member
station WGBH
reports, their trailer full of
food is making

49:57.962 --> 50:01.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a difference in the lives of
low-income families.

50:01.265 --> 50:04.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's also helping keep their
son's memory
alive.

50:04.602 --> 50:12.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TINA MARTIN: One smile and one
plate of food
at a time is how David and
Alicia Blais of

50:12.276 --> 50:14.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Framingham plan to knock out
hunger in their
hometown.

50:14.812 --> 50:15.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALICIA BLAIS, Daniel's Table:
Hi.

50:15.813 --> 50:17.314 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
How are you?

50:17.348 --> 50:18.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BLAIS, Daniel's Table:
Over dinner one
night, I was talking to Alicia.

50:18.649 --> 50:20.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I said, what if we just
solved it?

50:20.751 --> 50:23.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What would it look like if we
just solved
hunger in Framingham?

50:23.387 --> 50:29.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALICIA BLAIS: You know yourself,
when you're
hungry, you don't study well,
you don't work

50:29.793 --> 50:31.495 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
well, you don't think straight.

50:31.528 --> 50:35.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TINA MARTIN: The Greater Boston
Food Bank
estimates about one in 12 people
in Eastern

50:35.566 --> 50:38.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Massachusetts get assistance
with food.

50:38.702 --> 50:40.271 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Many are families with children.

50:40.304 --> 50:44.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That especially touched the
couple who started
Daniel's Table two years ago.

50:44.074 --> 50:48.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BLAIS: My son Daniel died
at birth 21
years ago.

50:48.412 --> 50:53.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when we started with this
project, we
thought that we would name it
after him.

50:53.083 --> 50:55.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's kind of a motivating factor
for me.

50:55.619 --> 51:00.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
